{"_id":"4vEZwnMQ8W2tBgu7","name":"Graal (& girallons)","permission":{"default":0,"r4bmbG4VWpj9A47k":3},"folder":"wf40lADkdvhEIKuG","sort":100000,"flags":{},"content":"<div>There's a zombie for graal and regular girallon&nbsp;</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<h2 id=\"characteristics\">Characteristics:</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>hates candy</li>\n<li>killed and ate a gnome after it offered her candy</li>\n<li>killed oubridthe, the lemure, by punching it into a puddle which sucked oubridthe down to hell</li>\n<li>can wield at least 4 swords at once ? (hoped for by Cyrowan)</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- --><!-- --><!-- --><!-- -->\n<h2 id=\"girallons\">Girallons</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>- Flick: Well there&rsquo;s Seomra Crann, but don&rsquo;t tell them we sent you. / - Graal: Heh. That&rsquo;s a common sentiment among the Girallon. It&rsquo;s considered polite not to mention who else you know as a shared friend.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- --><hr />\n<p><span style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\">Among the animals, the&nbsp;</span><a style=\"text-decoration-line: none; color: #0b0080; background: none #ffffff; font-family: sans-serif;\" title=\"Gibbon\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gibbon\">gibbon</a><span style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\">&nbsp;and the&nbsp;</span><a style=\"text-decoration-line: none; color: #0b0080; background: none #ffffff; font-family: sans-serif;\" title=\"Crane (bird)\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crane_(bird)\">crane</a><span style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\">&nbsp;were considered experts at inhaling the&nbsp;</span><em style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\">qi</em><span style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\">. The Confucian scholar&nbsp;</span><a style=\"text-decoration-line: none; color: #0b0080; background: none #ffffff; font-family: sans-serif;\" title=\"Dong Zhongshu\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dong_Zhongshu\">Dong Zhongshu</a><span style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\">&nbsp;(ca. 150 BC) wrote in&nbsp;</span><a style=\"text-decoration-line: none; color: #0b0080; background: none #ffffff; font-family: sans-serif;\" title=\"Luxuriant Dew of the Spring and Autumn Annals\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luxuriant_Dew_of_the_Spring_and_Autumn_Annals\">Luxuriant Dew of the Spring and Autumn Annals</a><span style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\">:</span><sup id=\"cite_ref-21\" class=\"reference\" style=\"line-height: 1; unicode-bidi: isolate; white-space: nowrap; font-size: 11.2px; color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\"><a style=\"text-decoration-line: none; color: #0b0080; background: none;\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qi#cite_note-21\">[18]</a></sup><span style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\">&nbsp;\"The gibbon resembles a macaque, but he is larger, and his color is black. His forearms being long, he lives eight hundred years, because he is expert in controlling his breathing.\" (\"</span><span lang=\"zh\" style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\" title=\"Chinese language text\">猿似猴。大而黑。長前臂。所以壽八百。好引氣也。</span><span style=\"color: #202122; font-family: sans-serif; background-color: #ffffff;\">\")</span></p>\n<!-- -->\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- -->"}
{"_id":"5d6CIL1ufTGwEBnl","name":".enumerative bibliography","permission":{"default":3,"akeJDKtMsE0KHFKm":3},"folder":"Cec7aiKp7sFrzQHB","sort":100000,"flags":{},"content":"<p>Dr. Sanctfeld Imst ∙ <em>Brown studies and similarly dicible mental turbations appertaining to coff&egrave;wort</em>&nbsp; ∙ 1697</p>\n<div><em>Inveterate Worm Rocks and the History of Insecure Foundations in the Blood Mountains.</em></div>\n<p>H.F. Wylmott ∙ <em>Commentary on the Diaschizdein Glaucous ☼</em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<hr />\n<p>☼ journal entry exists</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<section class=\"secret\">\n<h2>ideas</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Extracts from the account rolls of the Abbey of Durham&nbsp;(ed. Joseph Thomas Fowler) &middot; Surtees Society edition, 1898&ndash;1901 (3 vols.). (Publications of the Surtees Society 99, 100, 103).</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">The Fomblitudes [weak comparisons] of Manlius and Judas</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Ordinal of Alchemy</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Of Wisdom</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Occasional Reflections upon several subjects. Whereto is premi'd a Discourse about such kind of thoughts.</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Atomia &amp; Alchemy</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Hydrological Chimaera</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Origin of Forms and Qualities</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Compendium of Alchemy</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Logs of the Sea-Waif</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">[ ]: a certain supplicatory pathos</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Theatrum poetarum, or, A compleat collection of the poets especially the most eminent, of all ages, the antients distinguish't from the moderns in their several alphabets : with some observations and reflections upon many of them, particularly those of our own nation : together with a prefatory discourse of the poets and poetry in generall / by Edward Phillips.</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Scruples</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Decastich (DEH cuh stick) - a poem of ten lines</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">[god name] Unmasked or an Inquiry into the Nature and origin of the Passion of Love</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Samuel Rush Meyrick &middot; A critical inquiry into antient armour, as it existed in Europe, but particularly in England, from the Norman conquest to the reign of King Charles II &middot; 1st edition, 1824 (3 vols.).</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">The romance of Sir Beues of Hamtoun (ed. Eugen Kölbing) &middot; EETS edition, 1885&ndash;1894 (3 vols.); 1973 reprint (1 vol.). (EETSES 46, 48, 65).</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Fynes Moryson &middot; An itinerary..containing his ten yeeres trauell &middot; 1st edition, 1617 (1 vol.).</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">London: J. Beale, Fynes Moryson (?1566&ndash;1630)</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Matthew Hale &middot; The primitive origination of mankind &middot; 1st edition, 1677 (1 vol.). London,: Printed by William Godbid, for William Shrowsbery at the sign of the Bible in Duke-Lane.,</li>\n<li style=\"box-sizing: border-box; user-select: text;\">Charles Cotton &middot; Burlesque upon burlesque: or, The scoffer scoft, being some of Lucian's dialogues newly put into English fustian, by one who never transgressed before&nbsp;&middot;</li>\n<li>&nbsp;Resolutions and decisions of divers practicall cases of conscience &middot; 1st edition, 1